### Question 5 - Minimized the cost with norm L2

(For one cluster)

- $$cost(\mu) = \sum_{i = 1}^n || z_i - \mu ||_2^2$$ 

with $z_i$ = points in the cluster and $\mu$ the centroid of the cluster

- Then we calculate the gradient : $ \nabla cost(\mu) = \sum_{i=1}^n  -2(x_{i}-\mu) $ 

- And we are looking to cancel it : $ \nabla f(\mu) = 0 \leftrightarrow n\mu = \sum_{i=1}^n x_{i} $. 

So $ \mu = \frac{1}{n}  \sum_{i=1}^n x_{i} $

It shows that to minimize the cost with the norm L2 we have to take the mean of the cluster.

### Question 6 - Minimized the cost with norm L1

(For one cluster)

- $$cost(\mu) = \sum_{i = 1}^n || z_i - \mu ||_1^2$$

with $z_i$ = points in the cluster and $\mu$ the centroid of the cluster

- we calculate the derivative of the cost :  $ \ cost'(\mu) = -1*| \left\{ i : x_{i} < \mu \right\} | +1*|\left\{ i : x_{i} > \mu \right\} | $

- And we are looking to cancel it : $$ f'(\mu) = 0 \leftrightarrow | \left\{ i : x_{i} < \mu \right\} | = |\left\{ i : x_{i} > \mu \right\} |$$

It shows that to minimize the cost with the norm L1 we have to take the median of the cluster.

## Exercise 2 : Implementing k-means for color quantization

### Size of the image

The picture is 390*755 pixels large. The parameter d corresponds to the "depth" of a pixel, the number of components (3 for us : R G and B)

### Role of *m* and *n*

*m* is the number of samples, so it is represents by the number of pixels in the image, which is 
$$
w * h = 390*755= 294450
$$
*n* is the "dimension" we work in, which is 2. 

### `np.reshape`

This instruction converts the original picture in a list of size 390*755 of pixels (which 3 values for each). It allows us to compute is as a list, instead of an image, because this is how our algorithm uses data. To get an image back, we will use `np.reshape` again. 

### Complete functions 

- `calculate_centroids`: In this function, we compute the new centroids. So we need to sum and count the values in each cluster (sum the distance to the centroid). 
- `convergence` : In this function, we need to compute the difference between the old and the new inertia. 
- `KMeans` : We need to complete the iterative part of the algorithm. *codebook* represents the old centroids. We use the model given in the text. 

### Different parameters

Now we have a complete algorithm. We can try to adjust the parameters to have the better output as possible in a decent time. 

Let's chose : 
$$
threshold \in \{0.5, 0.3, 0.1, 0.01, 0.001 \} \\max\_iteration \in \{3,5,10,50 \}
$$
When we analyze what we get, we observe that the images are quite equivalent. There is no visual difference using those parameters. Pour `max_iteration=50`, the algorithm is very slow to converge (about 30 minutes), so this is not a very efficient way to improve the results.
